  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Expositor's Greek Testament",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 7:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". There are also two different kinds of teachers: the one ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀφʼ ἑαυτοῦ λαλῶν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", speaks his own mind, teaches his own ideas, does not represent God and reveal His mind; because he ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τὴν δόξαν τὴν ἰδίαν ζητεῖ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", “seeks his own glory,” which of course cannot be reached by representing himself to be merely the herald of another’s glory. The other style of teacher is described in the words ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ὁ δὲ ζητῶν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " … ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἔστιν",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Plainly He who seeks the glory of Him whose ambassador He is, has no interest in falsifying matters to advance His own interests. If His aim is to advance the glory of Him who has sent Him, He will truthfully deliver His message; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀληθής ἐστι",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "καὶ ἀδικία",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " … and injustice, dishonesty, is not in Him. The application of this general principle to Jesus was obvious.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Cambridge Bible for Schools and Colleges",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Proof almost in the form of a syllogism that He does not speak of Himself. It applies to Christ alone. Human teachers who seek God’s glory are not thereby secured from erroneous teaching. These verses (16–18) remind us, and might remind some of His hearers of an earlier discourse delivered in Jerusalem some seven months before: comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 5:19",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 5:30",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 5:37",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 5:44",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ".",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the same is true",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] and therefore does not speak of himself, for whoever speaks what comes from himself is not true.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "no unrighteousness is in him",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "] Or, ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "bld",
        "text": "unrighteousness is not in him",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". S. John does not say ‘falsehood’ as we might expect, but uses a wider word which points out the moral root of the falsehood. Comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 8:46",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". Throughout S. John’s writings the connexion between truth and righteousness, falsehood and unrighteousness is often brought before us. Hence his peculiar phrases ‘to ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "do",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " the truth’ (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "1 John 1:6",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "), ‘to do a lie’ (",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Revelation 21:27",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "Revelation 22:15",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ").",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "There is no need to suppose that anything is omitted between 18 and 19, though the transition is abrupt. Christ has answered them and now takes the offensive. He exposes the real meaning of their cavillings; they seek His life.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      }
    ]
  },
  {
    "type": "EXEGETICAL (ORIGINAL LANGUAGES)",
    "name": "Bengel's Gnomen",
    "elements": [
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 7:18",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ". ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "Ὁ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") Most sure characteristics. A syllogism; He who speaks of himself, seeketh his own glory, being untrue and unrighteous; but Jesus doth not seek His own glory, but truly the glory of the Father, by whom He was sent. Therefore Jesus doth not speak of Himself, but is true and worthy of belief.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "τὴν δόξαν τοῦ πέμψαντος",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "the glory of Him, who sent",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") Two things are here included; that He was sent; and that He seeks the glory of Him, who sent Him. The latter is the test of the former.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "οὗτος",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "he",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and he only.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀληθής",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "true",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", and to be esteemed as true.—",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "greekheb",
        "text": "ἀδικία",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "unrighteousness",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ") ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "falsehood",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": "; comp. ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "John 7:24",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": " [Judge righteous judgment], ",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "ital",
        "text": "true",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "",
        "text": ", righteous.",
        "children": []
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "p",
        "text": "",
        "children": [
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          },
          {
            "element": "br",
            "class": "",
            "text": "",
            "children": []
          }
        ]
      },
      {
        "element": "span",
        "class": "verse-link",
        "text": "",
        "children": []
      }
